    <div class="vs">
      <div class="bad">
        <div class="yr">1994 — the tax credit route</div>
        <h3>63 Tiffany Place</h3>
        <p>
          Public subsidy builds it. Seventy families move in. A thirty-year compliance period keeps
          the rent affordable. Everyone does everything right for three decades — rent paid on time,
          even through the pandemic.
        </p>
        <p>
          Then the term runs out. The building is an asset again. The tenants are a problem to be
          solved.
        </p>
        <div class="end">Thirty years later: fighting to stay.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="good">
        <div class="yr">The community ownership route</div>
        <h3>Cooper Square</h3>
        <p>
          Neighbours on the Lower East Side spent <strong>fifty years</strong> fighting Robert Moses,
          the real estate industry, and five mayors. They won the land, and put it into a community
          land trust and mutual housing association.
        </p>
        <p>
          There is no compliance period, because there is nothing to comply with. Affordability
          isn't a promise the owner made — it's a condition of the ownership itself.
        </p>
        <div class="end">Still home. Permanently.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pull red">
      It took Frances Goldin fifty years to win permanent affordability for her neighbours.
      We handed my landlord a thirty-year clock and called it housing policy.
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      Their fight is the subject of a documentary called <em>Rabble Rousers</em> — and I organized a
      screening of it, with New Economy Project, precisely so people could watch somebody win.
      <a href="/events/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">See the event →</a>
    </p>

    <h2>What a community land trust actually is</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      Strip away the jargon and it's simple: <strong>the land is owned by a nonprofit accountable to
      the community, not by someone trying to sell it.</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      Because nobody owns the land for profit, nobody has a reason to raise the rent to what the
      market will bear. The affordability isn't enforced by a thirty-year contract that somebody
      has to police and that eventually expires. It's <em>structural</em>. It doesn't run out
      because there's no clock to run.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      Tenants sit on the board. Tenants decide how the building is run. And in many cases the
      building converts to a limited-equity cooperative, where the residents collectively own their
      homes outright.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      LIHTC makes housing affordable for thirty years and then hands it to the market.
      A CLT takes it off the market permanently. That is the entire difference,
      and it is the whole argument.
    </blockquote>

    <h2>This is not theoretical. It is happening now.</h2>

    <div class="win">
      <div class="when">February 2024</div>
      <h4>East New York CLT buys a building. Privately. From a landlord.</h4>
      <p>
        The first community land trust in New York City to acquire a multifamily building on the
        open market. They call it a <strong>tenant takeover</strong>. The building is being
        rehabbed, the residents are being organized into a governing body, and it will convert to
        an HDFC cooperative — owned by the people who live in it.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="win">
      <div class="when">2020</div>
      <h4>East Harlem / El Barrio CLT acquires four buildings for $1 each.</h4>
      <p>
        Founded as a pilot project of NYCCLI with organizing support from Picture the Homeless — an
        organization founded and led by homeless New Yorkers. Four city-owned buildings, taken
        permanently off the speculative market.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="win">
      <div class="when">Now</div>
      <h4>Twenty CLT initiatives across all five boroughs.</h4>
      <p>
        Two decades ago there was one. This is the fastest-growing housing model in the city, and
        almost nobody in an expiring LIHTC building has been told it exists.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>So why isn't every expiring building doing this?</h2>
    <p class="lead">Two reasons, and both of them are fixable by people whose names you know.</p>

    <h3 style="margin-top:26px;color:var(--navy)">1. They don't get a shot at buying.</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      When your landlord sells, he sells to whoever he wants. A nonprofit that wants to preserve
      the building has no right to bid, no right to match, and — as we learned firsthand — often
      can't even get the access it needs to complete an appraisal.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      That is what <strong>COPA</strong> fixes at the city level and <strong>TOPA</strong> fixes at
      the state level: a first opportunity to buy, and a right to match a competing offer.
      <strong>COPA reached 26 Council sponsors — a majority — within one week of being
      reintroduced.</strong> It has passed the Council once already and was vetoed. It can pass again.
    </p>

    <h3 style="margin-top:26px;color:var(--navy)">2. Even when they get the shot, they don't have the money.</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      In April 2025 the city relaunched its acquisition and rehab funding program — the pot of money
      a nonprofit would use to buy a building like mine.
    </p>

    <div class="pull red">
      It was capitalized at $13 million.
      <span style="display:block;font-size:16px;font-weight:400;margin-top:12px;opacity:.9">
        In a city where a single Brooklyn apartment building can sell for more than that.
      </span>
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      This is what it looks like when a government says it supports something and does not fund it.
      The right to buy is worthless without the money to buy. <strong>Fund acquisition at the scale
      of the crisis, or stop pretending preservation is a priority.</strong>
    </p>

    <h2>If you're in an expiring building, this is your path</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      Not the only one — but the only one where you end up owning the outcome instead of hoping
      about it. Start now. A nonprofit needs years, not months, to assemble financing.
    </p>

    <h3 style="margin-top:30px;color:var(--navy)">The people who have actually done this, 1,600 times</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      There is an organization in this city that has spent fifty years turning distressed rental
      buildings into permanently affordable co-ops owned by the people who live in them. Almost
      nobody in an expiring LIHTC building has been told they exist.
    </p>

    <div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--line);border-left:6px solid var(--gold);border-radius:20px;padding:28px 30px;margin-top:20px">
      <h4 style="font-size:22px;color:var(--navy)"><a href="https://www.uhab.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--navy)">UHAB — Urban Homesteading Assistance Board</a></h4>
      <p style="margin-top:10px;font-size:17px;color:#243247;line-height:1.75">
        Founded in 1973. They have guided roughly <strong>1,600 buildings</strong> from distressed
        rental into affordable cooperative ownership, created over <strong>1,300 HDFC co-ops</strong>
        housing more than <strong>30,000 New Yorkers</strong> — and on their conversion pipeline they
        report a <strong>99% success rate</strong>.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-top:12px;font-size:17px;color:#243247;line-height:1.75">
        They will come to your building. They run training specifically for
        <em>tenants in a rental that is converting to a co-op</em> — how to govern it, how to budget
        it, how to run it. They give small loans to first-time co-op buyers. They keep a revolving
        Defense Fund for tenants facing dangerous conditions. And through
        <strong>HOPE — Housing Organizers for People Empowerment</strong>, a member-led program,
        they train tenants in negotiation, legal rights, and collective action. HOPE has built more
        than twenty tenant associations in East Brooklyn alone, winning repairs, rent overcharge
        refunds, and negotiated rent reductions.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-top:14px;font-size:16px">
        <a href="tel:2124793333" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:800;font-size:18px">212-479-3333</a>
        &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        <a href="https://www.uhab.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">uhab.org</a>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="note" style="margin-top:20px">
      <b>Understand how the pieces fit, because the jargon hides a simple idea.</b>
      An <strong>HDFC co-op</strong> is the vehicle — the residents collectively own the building,
      and resale prices are capped so it stays affordable for whoever comes next. A
      <strong>community land trust</strong> can hold the land underneath it, locking that
      affordability in permanently. <strong>UHAB</strong> is the organization that knows how to
      actually do the conversion, and has done it 1,600 times. <strong>COPA and TOPA</strong> are
      the laws that would give you the chance to buy in the first place. They are not competing
      answers. They are the same answer, in layers.
    </div>

    <h3 style="margin-top:34px;color:var(--navy)">And the organizers who convene the movement</h3>

    <div class="orgs" style="margin-top:26px">
      <div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:18px;padding:24px 26px">
        <h4 style="font-size:18px;color:var(--navy)"><a href="https://www.neweconomyproject.org/our-work/campaigns-and-coalitions/community-land-trusts/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--navy)">New Economy Project</a></h4>
        <p style="margin-top:8px;font-size:16px;color:var(--slate);line-height:1.7">
          They co-founded and convene NYCCLI, and they provide one-on-one organizing support plus
          legal and technical assistance to groups trying to form or join a CLT. They also run a
          loan fund that invests directly. If you want your building to end up community-owned,
          <strong>this is the first call.</strong><br>
          <a href="mailto:info@neweconomyproject.org" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">info@neweconomyproject.org</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:18px;padding:24px 26px;margin-top:14px">
        <h4 style="font-size:18px;color:var(--navy)"><a href="https://nyccli.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--navy)">NYCCLI</a> <span style="font-weight:400;color:var(--slate);font-size:15px">— New York City Community Land Initiative (say "nicely")</span></h4>
        <p style="margin-top:8px;font-size:16px;color:var(--slate);line-height:1.7">
          The alliance of CLTs and housing justice groups. They run workshops and will come and
          present to your tenants association. They also co-lead COPA and, with Housing Justice for
          All, coordinate the statewide TOPA working group.<br>
          <a href="mailto:info.nyccli@gmail.com" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">info.nyccli@gmail.com</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:18px;padding:24px 26px;margin-top:14px">
        <h4 style="font-size:18px;color:var(--navy)"><a href="https://www.neweconomyproject.org/cltmap/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--navy)">Find the CLT near you</a></h4>
        <p style="margin-top:8px;font-size:16px;color:var(--slate);line-height:1.7">
          A map of every community land trust in New York City, built by New Economy Project with
          NYCCLI. There are twenty. One of them is probably in your neighborhood.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="note" style="margin-top:36px">
      <b>Be realistic about the timeline.</b>
      A CLT acquisition is slow, difficult, and depends on financing that is currently
      underfunded. It is not a rescue that arrives when you call. It is a campaign you start years
      before you need it — which is exactly why I'm telling you now, and not when your notice
      arrives.
    </div>

    <h2>And support the Community Land Act</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      NYCCLI's legislative package — the whole thing, not just the piece that helps my building:
    </p>
    <ul style="margin-top:16px;padding-left:22px">
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:10px;color:#243247"><strong>COPA</strong> — a first opportunity for CLTs and mission-driven nonprofits to buy at-risk multifamily buildings when a landlord sells.</li>
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:10px;color:#243247"><strong>TOPA</strong> — the same right, for tenants themselves, at the state level.</li>
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:10px;color:#243247"><strong>Public Land for Public Good</strong> — prioritize CLTs and nonprofits when the city disposes of public land, instead of handing it to for-profit developers.</li>
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:10px;color:#243247"><strong>Abolish and replace the tax lien sale</strong> — a Giuliani-era policy that has extracted wealth from Black and brown neighborhoods for thirty years.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="pull">
      Every expiring LIHTC building is a building that could become permanently affordable
      instead of permanently lost. The only thing standing in the way is a right to buy
      and the money to do it.
    </div>

  </div>
</main>

